separate heads:
Anterior Deltoid (Front
Shoulder)

up the shoulder play a different role

BIG MISTAKE…
You aren’t taking advantage of this SIGNIFICANT muscle properly.
The rear deltoid moves your arm backward and helps with any and
all pulling movements. Allowing our shoulder to stabilize during
back-focused movements.
By building Rear Deltoid STRONG…your posture improves as a side
effect, preventing your shoulders to round and as a direct result of
that …we balance out the much more dominant head (front deltoid)
to reduce our risk for shoulder injuries.
And as an added side bonus if you build these properly ... .your
bench, shoulder press, and back lifts would BLOW TF UP! 
And those round & capped out shoulders that you think are only
reserved for steroid abusers? 
Yeah you’d have those too without the risk of heart failure and an
early grave.
This is why I am a Rear Delt Supremacist because there is a lot of
gains you are leaving on the table by not prioritizing this head of the
deltoid

This area of the muscle sits just below the upper trapezius… going

Having strong shoulders that can lift obscene weight is mainly about
exercise selection. But as you get stronger, (the more output your
body is capable of) the more can go wrong. 
Just like a Supercar (and we can use a Mclaren as an example) is
known to break down more often than Toyota. 
Why? 
Because the output the Mclaren is capable of is multiples more than
a Toyota Camry… which means more can go wrong.
But the good news is we have FULL CONTROL over the tiny nuts
and bolts involved in this entire system. 
Personal story, I was military pressing 185 lbs for reps and I was
proud of this because it felt like I was finally turning the corner. After
doing this for a few weeks I went to conduct my business as usual…
feeling great. I went to press and my trap pulled on me and I was
out of the gym for a few weeks as a result. When we injure
ourselves, we tend to get frustrated which is normal. But instead of
thinking of it as a setback… think of it as your body’s feedback to
report to you that there are things to fix.
I swear to you, every time I thought of it in this way…I’d go on to fix
the problem (injury) & my muscles and strength would BLOW past
my previous markers. Felt like magic and when I realized the
significance of these “annoying little muscles” I began to actually
look forward to it.
Because it requires such little effort to get these muscles up to
speed. Strengthen your rear delts, middle traps, & your lower traps…
And watch how strong you get.

You should be training the back of your shoulders as the very first
thing you do then move towards the front of your shoulders.
Again…think of it like soldiers in a war. 
The more soldiers you have going into a war the better off you will be. 
Problem is you have no defense system. 
Your defense system, your soldiers are the muscles on the back of
your shoulders through your upper back. 
If you don't have those in line, then the building will fall. 
First thing you want to do is start with a REAR DELT movement.
Why? Because this muscle is much more than the “accessory” or
“second-thought” muscle that everyone thinks. 
This is the first line of defense against shoulder injuries. 
You should be actively trying to get stronger on these lifts. 
These aren’t just “I will touch ’em up a little at the end”. 
Even if you don’t have injuries, this is an INTEGRAL part of the
shoulder that needs to be PRIORITIZED.
Get stronger on these lifts, get your numbers up and take it to failure. 
From there you can now enter the second part of the shoulder - the
side portion of your shoulder (Lateral Head).
This is the MOST aesthetic portion of the shoulder.
Giving you that “shoulder look” you are looking for.
